Troubleshooting Tips
TruffleHog not finding secrets:

Ensure files are committed to Git repository
Verify both --regex and --entropy flags are enabled
Check that test files contain actual sensitive patterns
Tika server connection errors:

Confirm Java is installed: java -version
Verify Tika server is running: ps aux | grep tika
Check port 9998 is not in use: netstat -tuln | grep 9998
Restart server if needed: pkill -f tika && java -jar tika-server-standard-2.9.1.jar --port=9998 &
Python import errors:

Install missing packages: pip3 install truffleHog tika
Verify Python version: python3 --version (should be 3.10+)
Check PATH includes pip installation directory
Empty scan results:

Verify target directory exists and contains files
Ensure Git repository is properly initialized
Check file permissions allow reading
Conclusion
This lab demonstrated practical techniques for detecting sensitive data in code repositories using industry-standard tools. TruffleHog provides powerful secret detection through regex patterns and entropy analysis, while Apache Tika enables comprehensive file classification and content extraction. By combining these tools with Python automation, you've created a reusable security scanning framework.

Key Takeaways:

Automated secret detection prevents credential leaks
Multiple detection methods (regex, entropy, patterns) improve coverage
File classification helps prioritize security reviews
Risk-based analysis focuses attention on critical issues
Continuous scanning should be integrated into development workflows
